---
import Page from '~/layouts/Page.astro';
import DownloadTable from '~/components/DownloadTable.astro';
import { VERSION, releaseUrl, releasesIndexUrl } from '~/lib/releases';
---

<Page
  title="Download — DataSUS ETL"
  description="Native installers for Windows, macOS, and Linux."
  locale="en"
  currentKey="download"
  ptPath="/download"
>
  <section class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 pt-16 md:pt-24 pb-24">
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-12 gap-10">
      <div class="lg:col-span-8">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-muted">
          <span class="pill pill-brand"><span class="pill-dot"></span>Release</span>
          <span class="pill pill-mono">v{VERSION}</span>
        </div>
        <h1 class="mt-5 text-display-lg text-text font-semibold">Native installers.</h1>
        <p class="mt-4 text-lead text-muted max-w-[58ch] leading-relaxed">
          Each installer ships a self-contained binary — no Python,
          DuckDB, or toolchain required on your machine. Download, run,
          click the shortcut.
        </p>

        <DownloadTable locale="en" />

        <p class="mt-4 text-xs text-muted">
          Released on GitHub:
          <a href={releaseUrl()} class="text-brand hover:text-brand-hover border-b border-brand/40 hover:border-brand-hover">v{VERSION}</a> ·
          <a href={releasesIndexUrl()} class="text-brand hover:text-brand-hover border-b border-brand/40 hover:border-brand-hover">all releases</a>.
          Verify checksums with
          <code class="font-mono text-text bg-surface-2 border border-border px-1 rounded text-[0.85em]">sha256sum</code> (Linux),
          <code class="font-mono text-text bg-surface-2 border border-border px-1 rounded text-[0.85em]">shasum -a 256</code> (macOS), or
          <code class="font-mono text-text bg-surface-2 border border-border px-1 rounded text-[0.85em]">Get-FileHash</code> (PowerShell).
        </p>
      </div>

      <aside class="lg:col-span-4 card p-6">
        <div class="label-stamp-strong">Unsigned installers</div>
        <h2 class="mt-2 text-display text-text font-semibold">A one-time click.</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-muted leading-relaxed">
          Code-signing certificates cost money; this project doesn't
          carry that cost yet. The first time you run the installer:
        </p>
        <dl class="mt-5 space-y-4 text-sm">
          <div>
            <dt class="label-stamp text-brand">Windows</dt>
            <dd class="mt-1 text-text leading-relaxed">
              SmartScreen shows a blue banner. Click <b>More info</b>, then
              <b>Run anyway</b>.
            </dd>
          </div>
          <div>
            <dt class="label-stamp text-brand">macOS</dt>
            <dd class="mt-1 text-text leading-relaxed">
              Gatekeeper blocks the first launch. Right-click the app in
              <b>/Applications</b> and choose <b>Open</b>; confirm.
              Subsequent launches work normally.
            </dd>
          </div>
          <div>
            <dt class="label-stamp text-brand">Linux</dt>
            <dd class="mt-1 text-text leading-relaxed">
              AppImages need the executable bit: <code class="font-mono bg-surface-2 border border-border px-1 rounded text-[0.85em]">chmod +x</code>
              the file, then double-click or run it directly.
            </dd>
          </div>
        </dl>
      </aside>
    </div>

    <!-- ===================================================================
         Intel Mac — source install walkthrough
         =================================================================== -->
    <section id="intel-mac" class="mt-24 pt-10 border-t border-border grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-10 scroll-mt-24">
      <div class="md:col-span-5">
        <div class="label-stamp-strong">Intel Mac users</div>
        <h2 class="mt-2 text-display-lg text-text font-semibold">No native installer —<br /><span class="text-brand">build from source.</span></h2>
        <p class="mt-4 text-muted leading-relaxed max-w-prose-tech">
          We ship a native <code class="font-mono text-text bg-surface-2 border border-border px-1 rounded text-[0.85em]">.dmg</code>
          only for Macs with Apple Silicon (M-series chips). If your Mac
          has an Intel processor, follow the steps on the right to
          install from source — it works, it uses exactly the same code,
          and takes about five minutes of terminal time. No programming
          experience required.
        </p>
        <aside class="note mt-6">
          <div class="label-stamp text-brand">How to check</div>
          <p class="!mt-2 text-sm text-muted leading-relaxed">
            Click the Apple logo → <b>About This Mac</b>. If it says
            "Apple M1/M2/M3/M4…", use the DMG in the table above. If it
            says "Intel Core i…", follow the steps on the right.
          </p>
        </aside>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-7 prose-tech">
        <h3 class="!mt-0 !border-t-0 !pt-0">Step-by-step</h3>
        <ol class="intel-steps">
          <li>
            <b>Install Python 3.11 or newer.</b> Open the
            <a href="https://www.python.org/downloads/macos/">python.org downloads page</a>
            and run the latest <b>macOS 64-bit universal2</b> installer
            (<code>3.11.x</code> or <code>3.12.x</code>).
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Open the Terminal app</b> (<kbd>⌘</kbd>+<kbd>Space</kbd> →
            type <code>Terminal</code> → Return) and run:
            <pre><code>{`pip install datasus-etl`}</code></pre>
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Pick a tutorial</b> for how you want to use it:
            <ul class="!mt-2 !mb-0 !pl-5 list-disc space-y-1">
              <li>
                <a href="./docs/cli/">CLI workflow →</a>
                — terminal commands, scripts, automation.
              </li>
              <li>
                <a href="./docs/python-api/">Python library →</a>
                — import as a module from your own scripts or notebooks.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <aside class="note">
          <div class="label-stamp text-brand">Hit a snag?</div>
          <p class="!mt-2 text-sm text-muted">
            If a step fails, copy the exact error message and
            <a href="https://github.com/nyckmaia/datasus-etl/issues/new">open an issue on GitHub</a>.
            Include the line of your Terminal that failed — we'll help.
          </p>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ===================================================================
         Technical package contents
         =================================================================== -->
    <section class="mt-24 pt-10 border-t border-border grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-10">
      <div class="md:col-span-5">
        <div class="label-stamp-strong">Technical</div>
        <h2 class="mt-2 text-display-lg text-text font-semibold">Package contents</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-7 prose-tech">
        <p class="!mt-0">
          Each installer bundles the same Nuitka-compiled binary — the
          app you run is the same one across platforms. The installer
          places the files in the OS-standard location, creates a
          shortcut to launch <code>datasus ui</code>, and (if you leave
          the checkbox marked) adds the <code>datasus</code> CLI to your
          <code>PATH</code> so commands like <code>datasus pipeline</code>
          work from any terminal.
        </p>
        <h3>On install</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Windows → <code>%ProgramFiles%\DataSUS ETL\</code> + Start Menu shortcut + optional <code>PATH</code> update (HKCU).</li>
          <li>macOS → <code>/Applications/DataSUS ETL.app</code> + optional symlink in <code>/usr/local/bin/datasus</code>.</li>
          <li>Linux → AppImage is self-contained. Run it from anywhere. A <code>.desktop</code> entry registers automatically when you place it in <code>~/.local/share/applications/</code>.</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>On first launch</h3>
        <p>
          The app starts a local web server on
          <code>127.0.0.1:8787</code> and opens your default browser.
          The server is loopback-only — nothing is exposed to the
          network.
        </p>
        <h3>User settings</h3>
        <p>
          Your data-directory preference and other settings are persisted
          in <code>~/.config/datasus-etl/config.toml</code> (Linux/macOS)
          or the equivalent location under <code>%APPDATA%</code> on
          Windows.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </section>
</Page>
